40|$|This paper {{examines}} <b>the</b> generational aspect <b>of</b> <b>the</b> current <b>Medicare</b> {{system and}} some stylized reforms. We find that <b>the</b> rates <b>of</b> return on Medicare for today’s workers {{are higher than}} those for Social Security and that <b>the</b> <b>Medicare</b> system is shifting a greater share <b>of</b> <b>the</b> burden on future workers than is Social Security. Nonetheless, <b>the</b> rates <b>of</b> return on <b>Medicare,</b> using <b>the</b> <b>Medicare</b> Trustees assumptions, are still not that high [...] roughly 2 percent for today’s youngest workers. But forecasting future Medicare expenditures is quite difficult. Under an alternative higher-cost baseline, which we consider plausible, rates of return for today’s youngest workers will exceed 3 percent. Putting Medicare on a sustainable basis by raising the payroll tax or reducing benefits would greatly reduce <b>the</b> rate <b>of</b> return for today’s workers. Under the Trustees assumptions, for example, the payroll tax {{would have to be}} increased by 2. 0 percent of payroll to put <b>the</b> <b>Medicare</b> system in balance in perpetuity. This policy would reduce <b>the</b> rate <b>of</b> return on today’s youngest workers to about 1. 3 percent...|$|R
