2500|$|According to the New York Times December 17, 2004 {{editorial}} W.J."Billy" [...] Tauzin, the Louisiana Republican who {{chaired the}} Energy and Commerce Committee from 2001 until February 4, 2004 was one <b>of</b> <b>the</b> chief architects <b>of</b> <b>the</b> new <b>Medicare</b> law. In 2004 when Tauzin was appointed as chief lobbyist for the Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers <b>of</b> America (PhRMA), <b>the</b> trade association and lobby group for the drug industry with a [...] "rumored salary of $2 million a year," [...] drawing criticism from a Washington-based Public Citizen, the consumer advocacy group. They claimed that Tauzin [...] "may have been negotiating for the lobbying job while writing <b>the</b> <b>Medicare</b> legislation." [...] Tauzin was responsible for including a provision that prohibited Medicare from negotiating prices with drug companies.|$|R
